These combined results further demonstrate that coal is one of ideal and unique carbon sources for the synthesis of CDs with high QY. As we all know, the anthracite features the macromolecular structure mainly made of sp2-carbon domains and adjacent layers linked by bridging bonds (Fig. 5
                     ). During the solvothermal process, light components in the anthracite are well dispersed in the solvent. Meanwhile, DMF could be partially decomposed to dimethylamine, which could be doped into the sp2-carbon domains via nucleophilic ring-opening reaction with the bridging bonds between the adjacent layers, thus leading to the exfoliation of small-sized sp2-carbon structures from the anthracite and the formation of the coal-based N-CDs [39,40]. Compared with the CDs made by acidic oxidation treatment, the as-made N-CDs via solvothermal approach feature relatively fewer oxygen-containing functional groups and more conjugated structure. Therefore, nonradiative recombination of electron-hole pairs is not dominated to some degree, thus producing a high QY [12,41]. Besides, the subdomains formed by solvothermal treatment are energetically favorable for the high QY, thus leading to strong intrinsic emission [15,16]. As a result, the coal-based N-CDs obtained by solvothermal approach exhibit a higher QY up to 47.0%, which is much higher than that of CDs made by acidic oxidation method and the surface-modified derivatives (Table S4). Moreover, the coal-based N-CDs could be dispersed in PMMA to form a monolith, keeping the inherent advantages of the N-CDs and the PMMA matrix (Fig. 6
                     ) [42–45].
